article.description: Lauren Jackson scored 27 points and the Seattle Storm overwhelmed the winless Phoenix Mercury on the backboards en route to a record-setting 97-87 victory.
article.headline: Six players in double figures for triumphant Storm
article.linkText: Jackson fuels Storm's record-setting win vs. Mercury
article.story:
SEATTLE (AP) -- Lauren Jackson scored 27 points to lead Seattle
to a 97-87 win over Diana Taurasi and Phoenix in a matchup of the
WNBA's two leading scorers Friday night.

Jackson, second to Taurasi in scoring, was 11-for-17 from the
floor with three 3-pointers and nine rebounds.

"We stepped up to the challenge," Storm coach Anne Donovan
said. "I think that's a good start for us."

Taurasi, averaging 23.3 points, was held to two points on
1-for-7 shooting in the first half after picking up two fouls in
the first three minutes of the game. She finished with 16 points on
5-for-13 shooting.

"Tonight we did a lot of good things, but there are still a lot
of things as a team well fix," Taurasi said.

Rookie Cappie Pondexter had 30 points for Phoenix (0-4), which
is still looking for its first win under new coach Paul Westhead.

This was the second win over the Mercury in nine days for
Seattle, which set a franchise record for points -- a week after
scoring 94 in Phoenix.

Jackson, who had a career-high 35 points in the previous meeting
May 25, had 10 second-quarter points including two 3-pointers
during a 19-7 run.

Seattle shot 51.5 percent for the game and scored the game's
first seven points. The Storm had field goals on six of their first
seven possessions in the second quarter and led by 15 at one point.

The Mercury got as close as 53-45 as Taurasi scored the first
four points of the second half -- and her team's first eight.

But Seattle extended its lead to 17 twice in the fourth quarter.

Phoenix then rallied to cut it to six three times as Pondexter
had six straight points.

Jackson reasserted herself with two straight baskets before the
Mercury cut the deficit to four points twice.

Seattle closed the game with free throws by Shaunzinski Gortman
and Tanisha Wright, plus a Jackson 3-pointer with eight seconds
left.
